      "created_at": "2026-04-02T10:22:45Z",
      "updated_at": "2026-04-02T10:22:45Z",
      "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body": "Minisketch-based implementation prototype at https://github.com/ajtowns/bitcoin/commits/202603-gettmplt/ ; seems to work on mainnet, but it's a ways away from being production-ready, and isn't specced/documented. Hmm, probably has a memory leak too? Anyway, rough idea of the approach:\n\n * `gettmplt` message requests a new template, possibly referencing a previous template from this peer as a basis\n * 8M weight template is generated by the peer at ~30s intervals; txs are represented by sorted 46-bit shortids  \n * `tmplt` response is given, indicating which entries from the previous template are still present, and include 4x 64-capacity minisketches of the shortids\n * can repeat `gettmplt` / `tmplt` three times, each of which divides the sketches in two, for an eventual total of 32x 64-capacity minisketches\n * if that doesn't resolve, a final `gettmplt` / `tmplt` round provides literal shortids (minus ~2048 entries, which are resolved via minisketch)\n * with shortids resolved, attempts to reconstruct txs from templates, mempool and extra pool\n * `gettmplttxn` message to request any missing txs\n * `tmplttxn` messages to supply the missing txs, each limited to ~100kB\n\nTransactions from templates are added to the mempool if possible, with 1p1c package acceptance where possible, and kept around for compact block reconstruction (and template reconstruction). `gettemplateinfo` and a field in `getpeerinfo` gives some insight, `gettmplt` log category does likewise. Delta to basis and request for missing txs are GR-encoded.\n\nSeems like the sketches have improved the bandwidth usage a bit as hoped, and so far seems like CPU usage is pretty reasonable.",
